default,000 
defaultto 18,000 
defaultpeople, provides data on the number of journeys per year made using different types of transport by residents of different types of area.  Figure 1 sh
defaultows the numbers of journeys for people of all ages.
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure 1  Jour
defaultneys per year by different means of transport and different types of area (National Travel Survey
default, 2003-05)
defaultThe total number of journeys increases slightly as the size of an urban area reduces, but is 
defaultsimilar
default for
default large urban areas (population over 250,000) to
default rural areas
default (settlements with 
defaultpopulations of less than 3,000)
default.  The number of car driver journeys increa
defaultses with reducing urban size
default and is particularly large in rural areas.  Walk journeys are similar in number across all urban areas, but fewer in rural areas.  Bus journeys are most frequent in London and the metropolitan conurbations, and very few in rural
default areas.
default&#xa0;
defaultAlthough the data in Figures 1 and 2 are for 2003-05, the situation has not changed greatly since that date.  Data corresponding to Figure 1 for 2011-12 is similar, with a small reduction in total trip numbers, a significant reduction in car use a
defaultnd increase in bus use in London, and a reduction in walking in the larger urban areas, but not in the smaller urban and rural areas.
default  In 2011-12, the total number of journeys in rural areas was fewer than in urban areas.
