default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultThe proportion of older people in isolated communitiesdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe ONS publication ‘Regional Trends’ publishes data on the proportion of people of retirement age 
defaultin individual local authority areas.  This makes it possible to determine the relationship between population density and the percentage of the population of
default retirement age.
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure 
default3
default shows this relationship for all local authorities in Great Britain in 
default2008.
default  The percentage ranges from almost 35% in some low density areas to under 10% in the hi
defaultghest density areas of
default Inner London.
default  The curve is similar, but le
defaultss extreme, for Wales on its own, and the range is even smaller for Scotland on its own.
default&#xa0;
defaultThese data show that older people are disproportionately located in low density areas, where it is difficult and expensive to provide public transport and other servi
defaultces, and where people depend on cars to reach the services and facilities that they require.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure 3   Population density and percentage of people of retirement age,
defaultfor local authorities, Great Britain  (Regional Trends)
